    "parsing_res_list": [
        {
            "block_label": "paragraph_title",
            "block_content": "## Chapter 2: Literature Review ",
            "block_bbox": [
                425,
                169,
                832,
                200
            ],
            "block_id": 0,
            "block_order": 1
        },
        {
            "block_label": "text",
            "block_content": "The field of Document Artificial Intelligence (DocAl) has evolved from simple character recognition to sophisticated Document Semantic Understanding (DSU) with interactive capacity. This section examines the progression from legacy OCR to deep learning-based architectures, evaluates preprocessing techniques, discusses secure deployment strategies.\n\n",
            "block_bbox": [
                210,
                262,
                1044,
                453
            ],
            "block_id": 1,
            "block_order": 2
        },
        {
            "block_label": "text",
            "block_content": "Early OCR systems used heuristic-based methods and template matching, utilizing tools such as Tesseract (v3.0 and earlier iterations) with polygonal approximation for text detection [1]. These systems showed critical limitations: traditional binarization techniques like Otsu's method [2] failed under real world conditions such as non-uniform illumination and low-contrast images, which resulted in elevated artifact generation and degraded character integrity, legacy engines lacked layout awareness and processed pages as linear text streams, causing errors when presented with a document with complex layout [3], and hand-crafted features proved inadequate for morphologically complex scripts such as Devanagari, leading to segmentation errors and high Character Error Rates (CER) [4].\n\n",
            "block_bbox": [
                211,
                509,
                1045,
                906
            ],
            "block_id": 2,
            "block_order": 3
        },
        {
            "block_label": "text",
            "block_content": "OCR systems with lower computational power and storage face a bottleneck when they are presented with high-resolution images . Targeted resolution optimization and RGBA-to-RGB color space conversion can help achieve substantial file size reduction while preserving character skeletal structure required for deep learning feature extraction [5].\n\n",
            "block_bbox": [
                210,
                964,
                1044,
                1153
            ],
            "block_id": 3,
            "block_order": 4
        },
        {
            "block_label": "paragraph_title",
            "block_content": "#### 2.1. The PP-StructureV3 Framework ",
            "block_bbox": [
                212,
                1211,
                657,
                1235
            ],
            "block_id": 4,
            "block_order": 5
        },
        {
            "block_label": "text",
            "block_content": "PP-StructureV3 represents a paradigm shift toward end-to-end deep learning for document understanding. As detailed in the PaddleOCR 3.0 Technical Report [6], this framework integrates layout analysis, table recognition, and structure extraction within a unified pipeline. Despite employing models with fewer than 100 million parameters, PP-StructureV3 achieves competitive accuracy rivaling billion-parameter ",
            "block_bbox": [
                210,
                1298,
                1044,
                1489
            ],
            "block_id": 5,
            "block_order": 6
        },
        {
            "block_label": "number",
